Yeah — four was just the core skeleton.
Once you look closer, the pattern family gets larger. Think of them as structural primitives that show up again and again across systems.

Here’s an expanded set that fits what you’ve been circling.

⸻

Structural patterns behind complex systems

1. Recursion

Structures containing smaller versions of themselves.

Examples
	•	fractals
	•	nested functions
	•	stories within stories
	•	hierarchical memory

⸻

2. Braids / Intertwining

Separate strands interacting without fully merging.

Examples
	•	DNA
	•	braided rivers
	•	counterpoint in music
	•	cross-linked ideas

⸻

3. Attractors

Stable patterns systems fall into.

Examples
	•	whirlpools
	•	planetary orbits
	•	habits in behavior
	•	cultural paradigms

⸻

4. Compression

Large information encoded in compact rules.

Examples
	•	DNA
	•	mathematical equations
	•	programming languages
	•	symbolic notation

⸻

Now adding more that usually appear with them:

⸻

5. Symmetry

Balanced structure that allows transformations without changing identity.

Examples
	•	geometric symmetry
	•	conservation laws in physics
	•	mirrored narratives

Symmetry often reveals invariants.

⸻

6. Feedback

Outputs feeding back into inputs.

Examples
	•	thermostats
	•	ecosystems
	•	markets
	•	neural networks

Positive feedback amplifies.
Negative feedback stabilizes.

⸻

7. Emergence

Complex behavior arising from simple rules.

Examples
	•	ant colonies
	•	flocking birds
	•	cellular automata
	•	economies

No single component contains the full pattern.

⸻

8. Thresholds / Phase transitions

Systems suddenly reorganize when a limit is crossed.

Examples
	•	water boiling
	•	avalanches
	•	viral memes
	•	technological tipping points

⸻

9. Networks

Nodes connected by relationships.

Examples
	•	neural systems
	•	the internet
	•	transportation
	•	knowledge graphs

Networks enable rapid propagation.

⸻

10. Gradients

Change driven by differences in intensity.

Examples
	•	heat flow
	•	electrical potential
	•	migration patterns
	•	information spread

Gradients create motion.

⸻

The meta-pattern

Most real systems combine many of these:

recursion
+ braiding
+ attractors
+ feedback
+ networks
+ thresholds
+ symmetry
+ gradients

Together they produce self-organizing systems.

⸻

Why your Charybdis metaphor fits

A whirlpool is actually many of these at once:
	•	attractor (center pull)
	•	gradient (pressure difference)
	•	feedback (rotational reinforcement)
	•	recursion (vortex inside vortex)
	•	network (currents interacting)

Nature loves reusing the same structural tricks.

⸻

The deeper observation

Across physics, biology, language, and culture, the same limited set of structural moves keeps appearing.

Almost like reality has a small grammar of complexity that gets recombined endlessly.

⸻

And interestingly, the Greeks captured some of this intuitively in myths like Charybdis and Scylla — chaos and structure shaping navigation.

⸻

